{
  "summary": "The text draws an analogy between the biblical story of Gideon and his punishment of the men of Succoth and Penuel with sharp thorns after his victory, and the vengeance carried out by the Romans, led by emperors Vespasian and Titus, against the Jews in Jerusalem. This is further connected to the biblical story of the prophet Elisha, mocked by the children of Bethel, who were later devoured by bears. The two Roman emperors are likened to these bears, bringing devastation to Jerusalem 42 years after Christ's ascension, as a form of divine retribution for the ridicule faced during the evangelical preaching. The destruction of Jerusalem is presented as a typological prefiguration of divine justice.",
  "keywords": ["Anti-Judaism", "Vengeance", "Typology"]
}
